1 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 2-8-301 of Title 10A, unless
3 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 This act shall be known and may be cited as the “Accountability,
5 Transparency, and Protection for Exploited Youth Act”.
6 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
7 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 2-8-302 of Title 10A, unless
8 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
9 A. Any employee, contractor, volunteer, or third party working
10 in or around a state-run juvenile facility, private contractor, or
11 group home under the supervision of the Office of Juvenile Affairs
12 or any county facility which detains juveniles, who becomes aware
13 of, witnesses, or suspects any form of sexual misconduct, coercive
14 relationships, or exploitation between staff, volunteers, or
15 contractors and juveniles, shall be required to immediately report
16 the incident to both the facility supervisor and the Office of
17 Juvenile System Oversight for independent investigation.
18 B. Any individual who fails to report such incident shall, upon
19 conviction, be guilty of a felony punishable by a fine not more than
20 Five Thousand Dollars ($5,000.00), by imprisonment in the custody of
21 the Department of Corrections for not more than two (2) years, or by
22 both such fine and imprisonment.
23 C. Investigation reports shall be forwarded to the district
24 attorney in the district where the abuse took place. The Office of
SB870 HFLR Page 2
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.
1 Juve nile System Oversight shall notify in writing the juvenile
2 victim’s family and the Senate and House of Representatives members
3 for the district in which the juvenile victim lives that the
4 investigation has been forwarded to the district attorney.
5 The district attorney shall notify in writing the juvenile
6 victim’s family and the Senate and House of Representatives members
7 for the district in which the juvenile victim lives when a decision
8 has been made to either file or decline to file charges.
9 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
10 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 2-8-303 of Title 10A, unless
11 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
12 A. Any employee, officer, contractor, or volunteer who
13 knowingly fails to report incidents of sexual misconduct or coercive
14 behavior shall be deemed to be acting outside the scope of
15 employment and therefore be subject to civil liability exempt from
16 The Governmental Tort Claims Act including, but not limited to,
17 damages for physical, emotional, and psychological harm caused to
18 the juvenile.
19 B. The Office of Juvenile Affairs and any contracted entity or
20 group home operating under the Office’s supervision shall be liable
21 for damages if a court of competent jurisdiction finds that the
22 employee, officer, contractor, or volunteer was negligent in
23 preventing, investigating, or responding to reports of sexual
24 misconduct. Liability for acts committed in violation of this
SB870 HFLR Page 3
BOLD FACE denotes Committee Amendments.
1 sect ion shall be exempt from the liability limitations under The
2 Governmental Tort Claims Act.
3 C. Negligence under this act shall include failure to properly
4 train employees on mandatory reporting, failure to respond to
5 previous reports, failure to terminate employees who abuse
6 juveniles, or failure to take action to safeguard juveniles from
7 known risks.
8 D. Juvenile victims, their parents or legal guardians, or next
9 friends may file civil actions seeking damages pursuant to the
10 provisions of this section.
11 E. Civil fines of up to Fifty Thousand Dollars ($50,000.00) per
12 juvenile victim may be levied against the Office, county facilities
13 where juveniles are detained, or contracting entities found to have
14 acted negligently.
15 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
16 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 2-8-304 of Title 10A, unless
17 there is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
18 A. The Office of Juvenile Affairs shall be required to provide
19 annual training for all Office employees, contractors, and
20 volunteers on the prevention, identification, and reporting of
21 sexual misconduct and coercive relationships between staff and
22 juveniles. Such training shall also be provided to employees,
23 contractors, and volunteers of county facilities where juveniles are
24 detained.
